Went here for a private Happy Hour from 6:30-8pm. When we arrived the front desk staff gave us wrist bands and explained how they worked. It was pretty simple. The drinks were very well made and not watered down. The service was rather quick considering how mane people were there and how few bartenders there were at the time.  A variety of food was also provided. My favorite was the hot Cheetos crusted chicken tenders. This was AMAZING. I don't even like hot Cheetos but I like spicy food but I gave it a try. I did not regret it. The Cheetos are crushed down to a very fine almost powder like texture. The chicken is fully covered in the Cheetos. It's a decent size chicken tender so the ratio to chicken to Cheetos was also just right. We also had the buffalo chicken tenders, mozzarella sticks, fries and buffalo chicken slider. All of those item were also just as good. Everything tasted really fresh and since most of it was fried I was afraid of how oily it could have been but nothing tasted overly oily or greasy.  Definitely recommend checking this place out. They have great music and the happy hour menu had a pretty good selection for a good price.

I visited Bounce on a Thursday night and it was crowded on the main floor with a number of groups.  When you first arrive, the exterior is sort of unassuming.. kind of a plain brown building -- no huge signage (it's just adjacent to Griddle 24 on Chicago Ave if you're having trouble finding it).. nice french doors.  It almost looks like a bistro.  But then you go inside and it's like the Tardis.. High ceilings, modern but comfortable booth seating.. (and lots of it).. and I was there for an event in a private room.  The security guy pointed to a wall and said, "it's through there."  But there was no door.. I mustered up all the faith I could and pressed on that wall and it moved!  The private room has it's own bar and when not in use, it's an easy flow portion off the main floor.  There's another lounge up a flight of stairs (or a ride in the elevator) that can probably accommodate about 20 - 25 people.. it has a sort of balcony that overlooks the back bar and seating area.  Since they just opened in November, they didn't get a chance to unveil their rooftop space -- so keep your eyes peeled for that debut later this spring!  They have a sister property in New York that's kind of a big deal -- so it's worth checking out on that alone.. but when you go inside, I think you'll be pleasantly surprised at the impressive "un-douchey-ness" of this welcoming and upscale friendly bar.  Now I have to tell you the bad news.  You're going to leave this place totally addicted to Banana infused Jameson.  I had no idea I would like it.. at first I thought "there's no way.. BANANA??"  but.. yes.  Banana. in Jameson. the sweet fruit kills that burny alcoholly sensation and makes this eternally drinkable.  It's best (I think) served on the rocks.. nursed like a sweet baby..  Seriously.  I dream about this stuff.  Drink it at your own risk.
